To draw a chessboard in LATEX, we can use the TikZ package, which provides a lot of options for drawing diagrams and graphics. Here's a complete code that uses TikZ to draw a chessboard:

```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\begin{document}
    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.5]
        % Draw the grid lines
        \draw[step=1cm,black] (0,0) grid (10,10);

        % Draw the starting position
        \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9} {
            \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9} {
                \draw[fill=white] (\x,\y) circle (0.5cm);
            }
        }

        % Draw the FEN notation
        \foreach \x in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9} {
            \foreach \y in {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9} {
                \ifnum \x>\y
                    \draw[fill=black] (\x,\y) circle (0.5cm);
                \else
                    \draw[fill=white] (\x,\y) circle (0.5cm);
                \fi
            }
        }
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

In this code, we first set the scale of the chessboard to 0.5, which means that each square will be 0.5 cm wide and tall. Then, we use the `step` option of the `grid` command to draw the lines of the grid. We set the `black` color for the grid lines and the `draw` option for drawing the grid.

Next, we use a nested loop to iterate over all the squares of the chessboard and fill them with black or white depending on their position on the board. We also use the `fill` option to make the squares look circular.

Finally, we use the FEN notation to fill in the starting position. We use another nested loop to iterate over all the squares of the board, and fill them with black or white depending on their position. We also use the `ifnum` command to check whether each square is in the right position for the starting position of a chess game.

